# County-Level Public Health Analysis in R

## Overview

This project analyzes county-level public health data to explore how socioeconomic, behavioral, healthcare access, and environmental factors relate to life expectancy across U.S. counties.

The analysis was completed using R and focuses on data cleaning, exploratory data analysis, visualization, correlation analysis, and regression modeling.

---

## Project Goals

This project was designed to:

- Practice real-world public health data analysis in R
- Develop skills in data cleaning and transformation
- Create professional data visualizations
- Explore relationships between social determinants of health and life expectancy
- Build a portfolio-ready data science project

---

## Research Questions

- How does median household income relate to life expectancy?
- How does education relate to life expectancy?
- How are smoking, obesity, poverty, and healthcare access associated with life expectancy?
- Which variables show the strongest correlations with life expectancy?

---

## Tools and Libraries

- R
- tidyverse
- ggplot2
- janitor
- skimr
- corrplot
- R Markdown

---

## Data Source

County Health Rankings & Roadmaps (2023)

Data includes county-level measures related to:

- Health outcomes
- Health behaviors
- Clinical care access
- Socioeconomic conditions
- Physical environment factors

---

## Methods

### Data Cleaning

- Removed missing county-level observations
- Standardized column names
- Converted character variables to numeric values
- Combined datasets using county FIPS identifiers

### Exploratory Data Analysis

- Summary statistics
- Missing value inspection
- Distribution exploration

### Data Visualization

Created visualizations examining relationships between:

- Income and life expectancy
- Education and life expectancy
- Smoking and life expectancy

### Correlation Analysis

Generated a correlation heatmap to evaluate relationships among key public health indicators.

### Regression Modeling

Built a multiple linear regression model predicting life expectancy using:

- Median household income
- Education
- Smoking rates
- Obesity rates
- Uninsured rates
- Child poverty rates

---

## Key Findings

- Counties with higher income and education levels generally showed higher life expectancy.
- Smoking, obesity, and poverty were associated with lower life expectancy.
- Public health outcomes appear influenced by multiple interconnected socioeconomic and behavioral factors.

